<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920220-0099</DOCNO><DOCID>920220-0099.</DOCID><HL>   Bush Moves to Restore   South Africa's Access   To Financing by Bank</HL><DATE>02/20/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>ALL BANKS, BANKING NEWS AND ISSUES (BNK)INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)INTERNATIONAL TRADE NEWS (TRD)</IN><NS>INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND ANALYSIS (IEN)TRADE ISSUES (TRD)</NS><GV>EXECUTIVE (EXE)</GV><RE>AFRICA (AF)NORTH AMERICA (NME)SOUTH AFRICA (SF)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The Bush administration, continuing to lifteconomic sanctions against the South African government,moved to restore that country's access to financing by theU.S. Export-Import Bank.   Mr. Bush issued a &quot;presidential determination&quot; stipulatingthat South Africa has made &quot;significant progress toward theelimination of apartheid&quot; and that he has decided to permit arenewal of Ex-Im financing. It's the latest step taken by theBush administration since last July to lift sanctions againstSouth Africa's white minority government. Although Democratsin Congress and several private groups objected to the move,the Bush administration decided South Africa is makingprogress since the Convention for a Democratic South Africa,which includes the government, the African National Congressand other political groups, began meeting last year toestablish guidelines for a democratic nation. Mr. Bush'saction doesn't require congressional approval.</LP><TEXT>   Other U.S. sanctions remain against the government,including a requirement that the U.S. veto World Bank andInternational Monetary Funding for the government, andmilitary sanctions. Ex-Im financing won't be available toSouth African agencies that implement apartheid or to privateconcerns that don't adhere to fair labor practices.</TEXT></DOC>